From mzyphur @end|ng |rom |n@t@t@@org  Sat Oct 12 03:22:03 2024
From: mzyphur @end|ng |rom |n@t@t@@org (Michael Zyphur)
Date: Sat, 12 Oct 2024 12:22:03 +1100
Subject: [R-sig-eco] Using GLMs or GLMMs for diversity metrics?
In-Reply-To: <CAP+=Be1jJ_qrckg7TC8fd7NFbwU=8Z4fkUoX-itrgjeNzRDBMQ@mail.gmail.com>
References: <CAP+=Be1jJ_qrckg7TC8fd7NFbwU=8Z4fkUoX-itrgjeNzRDBMQ@mail.gmail.com>
Message-ID: <CAFEsyOyB+JV_8ban4jNRz9=95F6L72fj0iLKkQ6y4OeuSoyaEw@mail.gmail.com>

Hi Alana

To analyze your species count data across multiple years and temperature
groups, you can use a combination of tools from the vegan package for
calculating diversity metrics and mixed models to account for repeated
measures and other factors.

You are already using the vegan package to calculate diversity metrics such
as abundance, richness, diversity index, and evenness - functions like
diversity() for Shannon and Simpson indices, specnumber() for species
richness, and custom calculations for evenness. Since mvabund is not ideal
for non-integer data, especially for diversity indices that are often
continuous, a different statistical approach seems warranted. Mixed models
can handle your fixed and random effects, as well as the distribution of
your count data.

Given your data structure (repeated measures across sites and years), a
mixed model approach using the glmmTMB package in R seems appropriate,
given it can accommodate mixed models and various distributions, including
the negative binomial for overdispersed count data. Your fixed effects
would be temperature group (warm vs. cold) and year, whereas random effects
could be used for site since you have repeated measures from the same sites
across different years - assuming you want to treat these as random
conditional on the group and year fixed effects.

The glmmTMB package in R can be used for this, with plenty of example code
online, but maybe something like this for your case:

library(glmmTMB)
# Assuming 'data' is your dataframe with columns: 'diversity_metric',
'temperature_group', 'year', 'site'
model <- glmmTMB(diversity_metric ~ temperature_group * year + (1|site),
data = data, family = nbinom2)

The interaction between temperature group and year (temperature_group *
year) captures how the effect of temperature on diversity metrics changes
over the years, whereas the random effect (1|site) helps account for the
non-independence of observations within the same site.

Where I might be off, of course, please feel free to correct me!

Best wishes

Michael Zyphur
Director
Institute for Statistical and Data Science
